Additional Analysis for ExperiencesDashboard

Oluwasegun Apejoye

2023-02-06

1. Overlapping words

This shows relationships between the themes (the categories). It shows the categories that tend to be similar to each other in how they are assigned to comments i.e. how comments shared about one theme relates to another theme. These relationships are shown using the actual number of comments shared between the themes (comment frequencies) or the pearson correlation of the comment frequencies. Of particular interest is the correlation among theme, which indicates how often they appear together relative to how often they appear separately.

We used Network graph and heatmap for this purpose. In this sample report, the heatmap is used to show the relationship based on the pairwise correlation and the Network graph shows the actual comment frequencies. We can see how the Staff theme shows strong relationship to the Communication & involvement theme, this indicates comments relating to Staff often relates to Communication & involvement

NOTE: The heatmap will be available in the dashboard and users will be able to add the network graph to their report (available to download from the dashboard) if they find it more intuitive.

2. TF-IDF/Word counts

We’d expect the categories to differ in terms of topic and content, and therefore the frequency of words should differ between them also. The TF-IDF (term frequency-inverse document frequency) is used to quantify the relevance of words or phrases in a document amongst a collection of documents. Here we regard each theme/category as a document and we used the TF-IDF to find the prominent words peculiar to each of the category and we visualized the top 15 prominent words in each category.

3. Word co-occurence across categories

The Network graph above shows the top 5 words used in each category. The words friendly and staff has high present in comments labeled ‘Staff’. We also see how the “Mental Health Specifics” and “Medication” categories stand out compared to the linkage we see among other groups.

The above graph shows how the top occurring words (that are not stop words) within all the comments combined are distributed across the categories. We can see that among the top 20 frequent words in all the comments combined together, most occurred within comments tagged “Care received”. The words staff, helpful and feel account for most of the linkage between “Staff” and “Communication and Involvement” and “General” categories

4. Word-to-word connections

Above network graph shows the directional linkage between the most common bigrams (pair of consecutive words) in the whole data. It showing bigrams that occurred more than 5 times and where neither word was a stop word. The transparent of the arrows between the words are based on how common or rare the bigram is in the data.

friendly formed a major nodes and we see common short phrases such as Mental Health, friendly staff, and feel comfortable
